 are trying to decide between I and me, then the presence of the in the context probably does not help. [CLS] [SEP] By ignoring such words, we eliminate a source of noise in our discrimination procedure, as well as reducing storage requirements and run time. [CLS] [SEP] To determine whether a context word cis a useful discriminator, we run a chi-square test [Fleiss, 1981] to check for an association between the presence of c and the choice of word in the confusion set. [CLS] [SEP] If the observed association is not judged to be significant,3 then c is discarded. [CLS] [SEP] The significance level is currently set to 0.05. [CLS] [SEP] Figure 1 pulls together the points of the preceding discussion into an outline of the method of context words. [CLS] [SEP] In the training phase, it identifies a list of context words that are useful for discriminating among the words in the confusion set. [CLS] [SEP] At run time, it estimates the probability of each word in the confusion set. [CLS] [SEP] It starts with the prior probabilities, and multiplies them by the likelihood of each context word from its list that appears in the ±k-word window of the target word. [CLS] [SEP] Finally, it selects the word in the confusion set with the greatest probability. [CLS] [SEP] The main parameter to tune for the method of context words is k, the half-width of the context window. [CLS] [SEP] Previous work [Yarowsky, 1994] shows that sma.ller values of k (3 or 4) work well for resolving local syntactic ambiguities, while larger values (20 to 50) are suitable for resolving semantic ambiguities. [CLS] [SEP] \Ve tried the values 3, 6, 12, and 24 on some practice confusion sets (not shown here), and found that k = 3 generally did best, indicating that most of the action, for our task and confusion sets, comes from local syntax. [CLS] [SEP] In the rest of this paper, this value of k will be used. [CLS] [SEP] 2 We are interpreting the condition "c. occurs within a ±k-word window of w;" as a binary f