llocations). [CLS] [SEP] The new case is if one feature is a context word, and the other is a collocation. [CLS] [SEP] Consider, for example, the context word walk, and the following collocations: (1) (2) (3) CONJ walk v PREP 7 1£ we use the U (xiy) metric instead, then d cision lists fall down on different examples; e.g., {its, it's}. [CLS] [SEP] 50 C on fu si on se t Ba sel in e Cwords Collocs ± 3 2 Dl ist Dlist R el y U(xiy) w he th er I i t s p a s t t h a n b e i n g e f f e c t y o u r n u m b e r c o u n c i l n s e b e t w e e n l e d e x c e p t p e a c e t h e r e p r i n c i p l e s i g h t 0 . 9 2 2 0.902 0.931 0 . 8 8 6 0.914. [CLS] [SEP] 0.981 0 . 8 6 3 0.862 0.945 0 . 8 6 1 0.861 0.909 0 . 8 0 7 0.931 0.965 0 . 7 8 0 0.791 0.853 0 . 7 4 1 0.747 0.821 0 . 7 2 6 0.816 0.887 0 . 6 2 7 0.646 0.646 0 . 6 1 4 0.639 0.639 0 . 5 7 . 5 0..575 0.807 0 . 5 3 8 0.759 0.730 0 . 5 3 0 0.530 0.840 0 . 4 4 2 0.695 0.789 0 . 3 9 3 0.754 0.869 0 . 3 0 6 0.726 0.932 0 . 2 9 0 0.290 0.812 0 . 1 1 4 0.455 0.318 0. [CLS] [SEP] 93 5 0.829 0. [CLS] [SEP] 98 0 0.808 0. [CLS] [SEP] 93 1 0.805 0. [CLS] [SEP] 93 2 0.892 0. [CLS] [SEP] 96 7 0.961 0. [CLS] [SEP] 84 2 0.933 0. [CLS] [SEP] 82 1 0.654 0. [CLS] [SEP] 86 8 0.896 0. [CLS] [SEP] 62 9 0.667 0. [CLS] [SEP] 62 7 0.651 0. [CLS] [SEP] 80 [CLS] [SEP] 0. [CLS] [SEP] 65 9 0.800 0. [CLS] [SEP] 84 0 0.840 0. [CLS] [SEP] 78 9 0.726 0. [CLS] [SEP] 85 2 0.836 0. [CLS] [SEP] 91 4 0.906 0. [CLS] [SEP] 81 2 0.841 0. [CLS] [SEP] 43 2 0.568 Table 6: Performance of decision lists with the reliability and U(xiy) strength metrics. [CLS] [SEP] To some extent, all of these collocations conflict with walk. [CLS] [SEP] Collocation (1) is the most blatant case; if it matches the target context, this logically implies that the context word walk will match. [CLS] [SEP] If collocation (2) matches, this guarantees that one of the possible tags of walk will be present nearby the target word, thereby elevating the probability that walk will match within ±k words. [CLS] [SEP] If collocation (3) matches, this guarantees that there are two positions nearby the target word that are incompatible with walk, thereby reducing the probability that walk will match. [CLS] [SEP] If we were to treat all of these cases as conflicts, we would end up losing a great deal of (potentially useful) evidence. [CLS] [SEP] Instead, we adopt the more relaxed policy of only flagging the most egregious conflicts - here, the one between collocation (1) and walk. [CLS] [SEP] In general, we will say that a collocation and a context word conflict iff the collocation contains an explicit test for the context word. [CLS] [SEP] Table 7 compares all methods covered so far - baseline, two component methods, and two hybrid methods. [CLS] [SEP] (A sixth method, trigrams, is included as well-it will be discussed in Section 4.) [CLS] [SEP] The table shows that the Bayesian hybrid method does at least as well as the previous four methods for almost every confusion set. [CLS] [SEP] Occasionally it scores slightly less than collocations; this appears to be due to some averaging effect where noisy context words are dragging it down. [CLS] [SEP] Occasionally too it scores less than decision lists, but never by much; on the whole, it yields a modest but consistent improvement, and in the case of {between, among}, a sizable improvement. [CLS] [SEP] We believe the improvement is due to considering all of the evidence, rather than just the single strongest piece, which makes the method more robust to inaccurate judgements about which piece of evidence is "strongest". [CLS] [SEP] 51 C on fu si on se t B as eli 11 e C w or ds Collocs Dlist Bayes ± 3 : : ; 2 R e l y R e l y Trigra ms w he th er I i t s p a s t t h a n b e i n g e f f e c t y o u r n u m b e r c o u n c i l n s e b e t w e e n l e d e x c e p t p e a c e t h e r e p r i n c i p l e s i g h t 0 . 9 2 2 0 . 8 8 6 0 . 8 6 3 0 . 8 6 1 0 . 8 0 7 0 . 7 8 0 0 . 7 4 1 0 . 7 2 6 0 . 6 2 7 0 . 6 1 4 0 . 5 7 